{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-topic-topic-tsx","path":"/topics/brain-central-nervous-system-cancers-recognition-referral/","result":{"data":{"firstChapter":{"id":"e241e306-2458-5047-b18e-04b7d1fc2308","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[],"depth":1,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 5a4ecd0c-6f85-4b6e-ab22-4deac5dd8dc9 --><h1>Brain and central nervous system cancers - recognition and referral: Summary</h1><!-- end field 5a4ecd0c-6f85-4b6e-ab22-4deac5dd8dc9 -->","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item f72f2c27-5c42-430e-bb43-03d9d767192e --><!-- begin field 685d280f-8237-4f85-9f7a-c82594201dd3 --><ul><li>Around 9000 new primary brain and central nervous system cancers are diagnosed each year in the UK.</li><li>It is seen in both sexes, and is one of the more common cancers in childhood and young people.</li><li>Symptoms include new-onset seizures, headache, nausea, drowsiness, visual change, and personality change.</li><li>In adults:<ul><li>Consider an urgent direct access MRI scan of the brain or CT scan if MRI is contraindicated (to be performed within 2 weeks) to assess for brain or central nervous system cancer in adults with progressive, sub-acute loss of central neurological function.</li></ul></li><li>In children and young people:<ul><li>Consider a very urgent referral (for an appointment within 48 hours) for suspected brain or central nervous system cancer in children and young people with newly abnormal cerebellar or other central neurological function.</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 685d280f-8237-4f85-9f7a-c82594201dd3 --><!-- end item f72f2c27-5c42-430e-bb43-03d9d767192e -->","topic":{"id":"aa7cf861-d312-5f9c-86ef-a46404a6f544","topicId":"6fc8f65b-ae32-4117-b08f-c714436d9403","topicName":"Brain and central nervous system cancers - recognition and referral","slug":"brain-central-nervous-system-cancers-recognition-referral","aliases":["Central nervous system and brain cancers - recognition and referral"],"chapters":[{"id":